<worksheet>
    <title> Session #6 (Sections 2.6 and 3.1)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
    <exercise> <!-- controlling workspace length is the best way to force page breaks on a worksheet -->
      <introduction>
        <p>
        Follow the steps below to find <m>\D \frac{dy}{dx}</m> for <m>\D x^{2}-y^{2}=1</m> using implicit differentiation.
        </p>
      </introduction>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  Step 1: Take the derivative of both sides of the equation with respect to <m>x</m>.     
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  Step 2: Move all the <m>\D \frac{dy}{dx}</m> terms to one side of the equation and the remaining terms to the other side of the equation.       
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="3in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  Step 3: Solve for <m>\D \frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
           Use the graph below to answer parts (a) through (d), writing <em>increasing</em> or <em>decreasing</em> in the blank.  
        </p>
        <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session6_Fig1.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription> Graph of a function with five highlighted points. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              Starting from the left, the graph is increasing, passing through a point labeled <m>A</m> and reaches a point <m>B</m>.
              The graph then decreases, passes through point <m>C</m> and reaches point <m>D</m>. 
              The graph then increases, passes through point <m>E</m>, and continues increasing out of the frame on the top.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Between points D and E, the graph is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Between points A and B, the graph is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Between points C and D, the graph is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Between points B and C, the graph is <fillin characters="15" />.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    
    </paragraphs>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
    <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="1"><!-- must restart numbering manually for each section -->
      <statement><!-- #1 -->
        <p>
          Use implicit differentiation to find <m>\D \frac{dy}{dx}</m> for the curve <m>\D x^{3}+y^{2}=3x-y</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="1.5in" number="2">
      <statement><!-- #2 -->
        <p>
          Find the equation of the line that is tangent to the curve <m>\D (x-1)y^{2}=x+1</m>, at <m>(1.25, 3)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  
  
    <exercise workspace="2in" number="3">
      <introduction>
        <p>
           A cubed shaped block of ice is melting such that its volume decreases at a rate of <m>2</m> cubic centimeters per minute. 
           How fast is the length of one side of the cube decreasing when the side length is <m>5</m> centimeters? 
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Step 1 (Draw a Picture): Sketch a picture that represents the problem and label any variables of interest.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Step 2 (State Given &amp; To Be Determined Information): Identify (a) the given (or known) values for any variable or rate of change, 
               (b) the rates of change that need to be determined and at the specific values at which the rates need to be determined. 
               Be sure to include all units.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Step 3 (Formulate Equations): Look at the information collected in steps 1 and 2 to find a formula that represents the relationships
               between the rates and the variables. <em>Hint: For this problem find the formula that relates the volume of a cube to the length of its side.</em>
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Step 4 (Take Derivative): Use implicit differentiation to take a derivative of the equation in step 3 with respect to time, <m>t</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Step 5 (Substitute): Substitute all known values (see step 2) into the equation found in step 4, and then solve for the unknown rate of change.
            </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      
    </exercise> 

    <exercise workspace="2in" number="4">
      <statement><!-- #4 -->
        <p> 
         The length of a rectangle is increasing at a rate of <m>4</m> meters per second, and the width is increasing at a rate of <m>2</m> meters per second.
         How fast is the area of the rectangle increasing when the length is <m>10</m> meters and the width is <m>6</m> meters? 
         <em>Hint: Follow the same steps as the previous problem! </em> 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
    <exercise workspace="2in" number="5">
      <statement><!-- #5 -->
        <p>
         A company's profit, in dollars, is given by the equation <m>\D P(x)=100x-0.5x^{2}</m>, where <m>x</m> is the number of units sold.
         If the sales are increasing at a rate of <m>10</m> units per day, how fast does the profit change when <m>50</m> units are sold?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise> 
  
  
